nd","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Haye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Helmut, Willi.","North German, East Frisian, and Dutch: from a personal name, Frisian <i>Hajo</i>, ancient Germanic <i>Haio</i>; or from a short form of the female name <i>Hadewig</i>, composed of the elements <i>hadu</i> ‘battle, strife’ + <i>wīg</i> ‘war’.","German: variant of   Hey   4, 5."],"variants":[{"name":"Deshayes","meanings":["French: topographic name for someone who lived by an enclosure, from the plural of Old French <i>haye</i> ‘hedge’ (see   Haye   and   Hayes  ), with fused preposition and definite article <i>des</i> ‘from the’; or a habitational name denoting someone from Les Hayes, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Deshaies  ."]},{"name":"Hayenga","meanings":["East Frisian: patronymic from the personal name <i>Hajo</i> (see   Haye   1). It is formed with the suffix <i>-enga</i>, a variant of <i>-inga</i> (from the patronymic suffix <i>-ing</i> and genitive plural ending <i>-a</i>)."]},{"name":"Hey","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Hay  .","Dutch: variant, mostly Americanized (or archaic) and Flemish, of <b>Heij</b>, a topographic name for someone who lived on a heath, Dutch <i>hei</i>, <i>heide</i>.","German: metonymic occupational name for a grower or mower of grass, from Middle High German <i>höu</i> ‘grass, hay’."]},{"name":"Hayen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphonse.  German Heinz, Wilhelm.","Flemish, East Frisian, and North German: patronymic from   Haye   1."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":31,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705190,"age":62,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":87,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":100,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":109,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret de Haye was born in 1228, in Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom. She married 